To set the text color to red in CSS, you use the **`color`** property. You can specify the color using a named color, a hex code, an RGB value, or other color formats.

Here are the most common ways to do it:

### 1. Using a Named Color (Simplest)
```css
p {
  color: red;
}
```

### 2. Using a Hex Code (More precise control)
```css
p {
  color: #ff0000;
}
```

### 3. Using RGB Values
```css
p {
  color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
}
```

### Example in Context
If you want to apply this to a specific class in your HTML:

**CSS:**
```css
.error-text {
  color: red;
}
```

**HTML:**
```html
<p class="error-text">This text will appear red.</p>
```

You can place these rules in an external stylesheet (`.css` file), inside a `<style>` tag in your HTML `<head>`, or directly in an element's `style` attribute (inline CSS).

```sql
SELECT * FROM users;
```

To add an element to the end of an array in JavaScript, you use the **`push()`** method. This method adds one or more elements to the end of an array and returns the new length of the array. It also modifies the original array in place.

Here is a basic example:

```javascript
const fruits = ['apple', 'banana'];

// Add 'orange' to the end
const newLength = fruits.push('orange');

console.log(fruits);      // ['apple', 'banana', 'orange']
console.log(newLength);   // 3
```

You can also add multiple elements at once:

```javascript
fruits.push('grape', 'mango');
console.log(fruits); 
// ['apple', 'banana', 'orange', 'grape', 'mango']
```

If you need to add an element without mutating the original array (creating a new array instead), you can use the spread operator:

```javascript
const original = ['apple', 'banana'];
const newArray = [...original, 'orange'];

console.log(original);  // ['apple', 'banana'] (unchanged)
console.log(newArray);  // ['apple', 'banana', 'orange']
```
